## Researching Another Way

after searching on the internet again, i find that width specifiers can increase the number of printed characters without increasing the input size.

for example:

```c
printf("%4s", "hi");
```

prints:

```text
|  hi
```

which is 4 characters in total.

using the same idea:

```c
printf("%134513828x");
```

causes `printf()` to generate 134,513,828 output characters.

therefore `%n` will store:

```text
134513828
```

even though my payload is small.

to verify this, i create a small C program:

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main()
{
    unsigned int n;

    printf("%134513828x%n", &n, &n);
    printf("n = %u\n", n);

    return 0;
}
```

the output is:

```text
bc917188
n = 134513828
```

which confirms that `%n` stores the number of printed characters.

